Prescient \Pre"sci*ent\ (pr[=e]"sh[i^]*ent or -shent) 

a. [L. praesciens, -entis, p. pr. of praescire to foreknow; prae before + scire to know: cf. F. [rescient. See Science.]

Having knowledge of coming events; foreseeing; conscious beforehand.

 Pope.

Henry . . . had shown himself sensible, and almost prescient, of this event.

 Bacon.

Source: Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary (1913)